  abstract = {In this paper, extreme value theory is considered for stationary sequences {$\zeta$}n satisfying dependence restrictions significantly weaker than strong mixing. The aims of the paper are:(i)To prove the basic theorem of Gnedenko concerning the existence of three possible non-degenerate asymptotic forms for the distribution of the maximum Mn = max({$\xi$}1...{$\xi$}n), for such sequences.(ii)To obtain limiting laws of the form \$\$\textbackslash mathop \textbraceleft\textbackslash lim \textbraceright\textbackslash limits\_\textbraceleft n \textbackslash to \textbackslash infty \textbraceright{} \textbackslash Pr \textbackslash\textbraceleft{} M\_n\textasciicircum\textbraceleft (r)\textbraceright{} \textbackslash underset\textbraceleft\textbackslash raise0.3em\textbackslash hbox\textbraceleft\$\textbackslash smash\textbraceleft\textbackslash scriptscriptstyle-\textbraceright\$\textbraceright\textbraceright\textbraceleft{} \textbackslash leqslant \textbraceright{} u\textbackslash\textbraceright{}  = e\textasciicircum\textbraceleft{} - \textbackslash tau \textbraceright{} \textbackslash sum\textbackslash limits\_\textbraceleft s = 0\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft r - 1\textbraceright{} \textbraceleft\textbackslash tau \textasciicircum s /S!\textbraceright{} \$\$where Mn(r)is the r-th largest of {$\xi$}1...{$\xi$}n, and Pr{$\xi$}1{$>$}un{$\simT$}/n. Poisson properties (akin to those known for the upcrossings of a high level by a stationary normal process) are developed and used to obtain these results.(iii)As a consequence of (ii), to show that the asymptotic distribution of Mn(r)(normalized) is the same as if the \textbraceleft{$\xi$}n\textbraceright{} were i.i.d.(iv)To show that the assumptions used are satisfied, in particular by stationary normal sequences, under mild covariance conditions.},
